    <div style="border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:var(--radius-card);overflow:hidden;background:#fff;">
      <details class="sc-faq" open>
      <summary>What is chip-on-flex (COF) assembly?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">Building an electronic assembly directly onto a flexible circuit — surface-mount components, bare die and area-array packages on flex rather than a rigid board, so the finished part can bend or conform.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>What can Hana assemble onto flex?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">SMT components, wire-bonded bare die, and BGAs with underfill, plus die attach and glob-top encapsulation.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>How do you join flex to the rest of the product?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">By ACF (anisotropic conductive film) and hot-bar bonding — flex-to-PCB, flex-to-ceramic and COF-to-PCB.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>How are chip-on-flex assemblies protected?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">With conformal coating and glob-top / dam-and-fill encapsulation over bonded die.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>How is chip-on-flex different from chip-on-board?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">Same bare-die assembly approach — chip-on-board builds onto a rigid board, chip-on-flex builds onto a flexible substrate so the assembly can bend or conform.</div>
